       Morphing

       Several Aliens are capable of morphing from an inanimate object to
       their true form. These are shown in the Object data Legend as
       "Morphing" creatures. NOTE: Dr. Goldfire is a morphing creature
       ONLY in the final level (19). There is a special Goldfire code for
       this. Use of this code in any other level will not produce a
       morphing Goldfire.

       Activating Guards Early

       Normally, all actors become activated - go into "Attack Mode" -
       when one or two conditions are met. First, Stone would have to be
       standing or moving on the same floor code as an actor AND the actor
       would have to see him or hear a shot fired by Stone. Some actors
       are declared "deaf" by the use of floor code '6A'. So-called "deaf"
       actors do not react to shots being fired by Stone. They react only
       when they actually see Stone. This allows them to hide somewhere
       and ambush Stone unexpectedly.

       In Planet Strike, guards can have their status switched to Attack
       Mode by the use of a floor sensor. This sensor is the same one used
       to cause doors to open automatically and was named the "Auto-Door
       Hot-Spot" code (its name has been modified to reflect the change in
       its used in Planet Strike). When the sensor is pointed at a guard
       instead of a door, the guard switches to "Attack Mode" if he is
       non-deaf. If he is a "deaf" guard, his deafness is "cured" and he
       becomes a normal guard. Neither guard/alien is required to be on
       the same floor code as Blake.

       Barrier Activation

       All operable barriers (non-operable barriers are called Barricades)
       are activated by a switch somewhere. The switch can be turned on or
       turned off. (In Planet Strike, while most switches are placed in
       inaccessible locations, they don't have to be hidden). The switch
       is activated remotely in one of two ways: use of a floor sensor or
       the killing of a selected guard.

       Using the floor sensor method, you use a special floor code as the
       sensor and place an LHV (map coordinate) on top of each sensor that
       points to the switch. The switch can be located anywhere on the
       floor, but is usually imbedded in a wall close by or some other
       inaccessible location. The chosen floor code (009F for switch "on"
       or 00A0 for switch "off") then operates the switch when Blake walks
       over it. The switch has another LHV placed on top of it and points
       to the barrier that it (the switch) controls.

       The second method for operating a switch is to mark any actor with
       a map code (004F) that designates the actor as the "holder" of the
       switch "key". An LHV (map coordinate) that points to the barrier

                                     -19-
       
       switch, must be located adjacent to the actor (to his right).
       Again, the barrier switch has another LHV coordinate placed on it
       which points to the barrier to be activated. When the selected
       actor is killed, the switch position is changed and the target
       barrier is operated.

       NOTE: this feature can also be used to open doors or activate
       enemies. Mapedit will handle proper placement of the LHV in each
       situation.

       Fission Detonator

       A Fission Detonator (along with a Security Cube) must be used on
       every floor (except the last or a bonus floor). In addition to
       being positioned as a discrete object somewhere on a level, the
       detonator can alternately be carried by an actor by using map code
       004D where the actor is standing. When the actor is killed, he will
       drop the detonator for Blake to retrieve.

       LHV Use

       There's change with respect to where LHV's are inserted in Planet
       Strike. This change was mentioned above in the explanation of
       barrier switches. That is, an LHV coordinate is placed is the same
       cell as the switch; there is no need to have 'F8FF' placed on top
       of the switch, as in Aliens of Gold.































